{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496798"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:56:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:56:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1420"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1420"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.12,0.07,0.31,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1420"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101771"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1420"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1420"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84227"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7861"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1591"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1720"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7975"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42313"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101771"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-hour history of dull, pressure-like chest pain radiating to the left shoulder. He has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His medications include amlodipine and atorvastatin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with a pulse rate of 58/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Following appropriate workup, he is diagnosed with a ST-elevated myocardial infarction and managed appropriately with percutaneous coronary intervention and is now stable. His ECG on presentation to the Emergency Department is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely complication to result within the first 24 hours?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bradyarrhythmia","Dressler\u0027s syndrome","Rupture of the interventricular septum","Tachyarrhythmia","Papillary muscle rupture"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an inferior myocardial infarction, as evidenced by ST elevation in leads II, III, and aVF on the ECG. Understanding the vascular supply to different regions of the heart and the timeline of myocardial infarction complications is crucial for predicting likely complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBradyarrhythmia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely complication within the first 24 hours of an inferior myocardial infarction. The inferior wall of the heart is predominantly supplied by the right coronary artery (RCA), which also supplies the sinoatrial (SA) node in about 60% of people and the atrioventricular (AV) node in about 90% of people. When the RCA is occluded, as in an inferior MI, these conduction pathways can be affected, leading to various forms of bradyarrhythmias including sinus bradycardia, junctional rhythm, or AV blocks. The patient\u0027s presenting heart rate of 58/min already suggests early bradycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETachyarrhythmia\u003C/strong\u003E can occur after any myocardial infarction due to myocardial irritability, but is more commonly associated with anterior infarctions (left anterior descending artery territory) rather than inferior infarctions. While tachyarrhythmias can occur in inferior MI, bradyarrhythmias are more characteristic due to the specific vascular supply patterns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERupture of the interventricular septum\u003C/strong\u003E is a mechanical complication that typically occurs 3-5 days after an MI, not within the first 24 hours. It results from necrosis and weakening of the interventricular septum, usually in the context of a large anterior MI rather than an inferior MI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPapillary muscle rupture\u003C/strong\u003E is another mechanical complication that usually occurs 2-7 days after an MI. While the posteromedial papillary muscle is supplied by the RCA and can be affected in inferior MI, this complication would not be expected within the first 24 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDressler\u0027s syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (post-myocardial infarction syndrome) is an autoimmune inflammatory condition that typically develops weeks to months after an MI, characterized by fever, chest pain, and pericardial effusion. It is not an acute complication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe timeline of MI complications generally follows a pattern: arrhythmias (both brady- and tachy-) occur early (hours to days), mechanical complications occur in the subacute phase (days to weeks), and inflammatory complications like Dressler\u0027s syndrome occur late (weeks to months). Given the inferior location of this MI and the early timeframe specified, bradyarrhythmia is the most likely complication.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inferior myocardial infarctions commonly lead to bradyarrhythmias due to right coronary artery involvement affecting the SA and AV nodes.","ECG findings of ST elevation in leads II, III, and aVF are characteristic of inferior myocardial infarction.","Complications of myocardial infarction follow a predictable timeline, with arrhythmias occurring early (1-3 days) and mechanical complications later (1-4 weeks)."],"references":["Trappe HJ. Tachyarrhythmias, bradyarrhythmias and acute coronary syndromes. J Emerg Trauma Shock. 2010 Apr;3(2):137-42. doi: 10.4103/0974-2700.62112. PMID: 20606790; PMCID: PMC2884444. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2884444/","Rafla, S., Ayad, S.W. \u0026 Sanhoury, M. Study of Bradyarrhythmias in Acute Myocardial Infarction. Egypt. J. Critical. Care. Med. 9, 51\u201356 (2022). https://doi.org/10.1097/EJ9.0000000000000046","Warner MJ, Tivakaran VS. Inferior Myocardial Infarction. [Updated 2023 Feb 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470572/","Frampton J, Ortengren AR, Zeitler EP. Arrhythmias After Acute Myocardial Infarction. Yale J Biol Med. 2023 Mar 31;96(1):83-94. doi: 10.59249/LSWK8578. PMID: 37009192; PMCID: PMC10052595. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10052595/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84227"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1420"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19027"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19027"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aef87f22-2585-4c9d-955c-93356c8869ed.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aef87f22-2585-4c9d-955c-93356c8869ed.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":